notes.body:
You already trust BFS: it processes nodes in increasing distance order because a plain queue happens to keep them sorted when every edge costs 1. Weights break that free sorting — so Dijkstra swaps the queue for a **min-heap**, which hands you the closest unfinalized node in $O(\\log V)$.

> [!INTUITION] Ripples at different speeds
> Picture water spreading from the source, but each edge is a pipe of different length. The wavefront reaches nodes in order of true distance. The heap is just the machine that tells you which node the wave touches next.

The core loop: pop the cheapest node, **finalize** it, then *relax* each outgoing edge — if going through the popped node is cheaper than the best known route to a neighbor, record the improvement and push it.

One discipline makes the template clean: the heap is allowed to hold **stale** entries. If a node's distance improves after it was pushed, we don't hunt down the old entry (no decrease-key gymnastics) — we push a new, better one and let the old one surface later. When you pop `(d, u)` and `d > dist[u]`, it's outdated: skip it.

[[fig:m11-dijkstra-stale]]

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll,int> pli;   // (distance, node)

// adj[u] = list of {neighbor, weight}
vector<ll> dijkstra(int n, vector<vector<pair<int,int>>>& adj, int src) {
    vector<ll> dist(n, LLONG_MAX);
    dist[src] = 0;
    // min-heap: smallest distance on top
    priority_queue<pli, vector<pli>, greater<pli>> pq;
    pq.push({0, src});

    while (!pq.empty()) {
        auto [d, u] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        if (d > dist[u]) continue;        // stale entry — already found better
        for (auto [v, w] : adj[u]) {
            if (dist[u] + w < dist[v]) {  // relax
                dist[v] = dist[u] + w;
                pq.push({dist[v], v});
            }
        }
    }
    return dist;  // dist[i] == LLONG_MAX means unreachable
}
```

Complexity: $O((V + E)\\log V)$ — every edge can push once, every push costs a log.

> [!PITFALL] The whole catch: weights must be ≥ 0
> "Once popped, distance is final" is only true when no future edge can *reduce* a path's cost. A single negative edge silently breaks the guarantee — Dijkstra returns wrong answers without crashing. See any negative weight → switch to Bellman-Ford.

> [!NOTE]
> The same skeleton bends to variants: max-heap + multiplication for *Path With Maximum Probability*, `max(dist[u], w)` for bottleneck problems (deep dive below). Learn the skeleton once, swap the relaxation.

Special case worth its own reflex: every edge weight is **0 or 1**. "Cost to flip a cell", "walls you must break", "free move along the sign, 1 to go against it". Dijkstra works, but the heap's $O(\\log V)$ per operation is paying for generality you don't need.

With only two weights, the frontier only ever spans **two distance values**, $d$ and $d+1$. A `deque` keeps them ordered with zero comparisons:

- a **0-weight** edge keeps the neighbor at distance $d$ → push to the **front** (process before all the $d+1$ nodes),
- a **1-weight** edge sends it to $d+1$ → push to the **back**.

[[fig:m11-01bfs-deque]]

The deque stays sorted by distance automatically, so you pop nodes in nondecreasing order exactly like Dijkstra — in **$O(V + E)$**, no heap.

```cpp
vector<int> zeroOneBFS(int n, vector<vector<pair<int,int>>>& adj, int src) {
    vector<int> dist(n, INT_MAX);
    deque<int> dq;
    dist[src] = 0; dq.push_front(src);
    while (!dq.empty()) {
        int u = dq.front(); dq.pop_front();
        for (auto [v, w] : adj[u]) {          // w is 0 or 1
            if (dist[u] + w < dist[v]) {
                dist[v] = dist[u] + w;
                if (w == 0) dq.push_front(v);  // free move: front
                else        dq.push_back(v);   // costs 1: back
            }
        }
    }
    return dist;
}
```

> [!EXAM]
> Say it out loud: "weights are 0/1, so I'll use 0-1 BFS with a deque for $O(V+E)$ instead of Dijkstra's $O(E \\log V)$." One sentence, and the interviewer knows you're fluent, not pattern-matching.

When weights can be **negative**, Dijkstra's finalization promise is void, and Bellman-Ford takes over. It drops the cleverness entirely: relax *every* edge, and repeat that sweep $V-1$ times. Why $V-1$? Any shortest path visits each node at most once, so it has at most $V-1$ edges — and each full sweep is guaranteed to lock in at least one more edge of every shortest path.

```cpp
struct Edge { int u, v, w; };

// returns false if a negative cycle is reachable
bool bellmanFord(int n, vector<Edge>& edges, int src, vector<ll>& dist) {
    dist.assign(n, LLONG_MAX);
    dist[src] = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        for (auto& e : edges) {
            if (dist[e.u] != LLONG_MAX && dist[e.u] + e.w < dist[e.v])
                dist[e.v] = dist[e.u] + e.w;
        }
    }
    for (auto& e : edges)               // one more pass: still improving?
        if (dist[e.u] != LLONG_MAX && dist[e.u] + e.w < dist[e.v])
            return false;               // negative cycle
    return true;
}
```

Complexity: $O(V \\cdot E)$ — slower than Dijkstra, but it's the only correct tool for negatives.

> [!KEY] The V-th pass is a detector
> After $V-1$ sweeps every shortest path is done improving — *unless* a negative cycle keeps shaving cost forever. So one extra sweep that still relaxes something ⇒ negative cycle. That's the entire "can prices go infinitely negative?" question.

Bellman-Ford has a second superpower: **hop limits**. "At most K stops" means "at most K+1 edges", and since each pass extends paths by at most one edge, you just run K+1 passes — *on a frozen copy of the array*, so one pass can't chain several new edges.

[[fig:m11-bf-frozen]]

> [!PITFALL]
> Skip the frozen copy and a single pass can relay a relaxation through several edges — silently blowing your hop budget. The full trap (it killed many Cheapest-Flights submissions) is dissected in the deep dive below.

A **Minimum Spanning Tree** is the answer to a different question: not "cheapest route from A to B" but "cheapest set of edges that makes *everything* one connected piece". A spanning tree of $V$ nodes always has exactly $V-1$ edges — anything more contains a redundant cycle.

> [!ANALOGY]
> You're laying internet cable between villages. Every possible cable run has a price. You want everyone online for minimum total cost — and a cable that connects two already-connected villages is pure waste. MST = buy cheap, never buy redundant.

**Kruskal**: sort *all* edges by weight, walk them cheapest-first, and take an edge unless it would close a cycle. The cycle oracle is **Union-Find (DSU)** — the structure you built in Module 10: if both endpoints already share a root, the edge is redundant.

[[fig:m11-kruskal-scan]]

```cpp
struct DSU {
    vector<int> p, r;
    DSU(int n): p(n), r(n, 0) { iota(p.begin(), p.end(), 0); }
    int find(int x) { return p[x] == x ? x : p[x] = find(p[x]); } // path compression
    bool unite(int a, int b) {
        a = find(a); b = find(b);
        if (a == b) return false;              // already connected → cycle
        if (r[a] < r[b]) swap(a, b);
        p[b] = a;
        if (r[a] == r[b]) r[a]++;
        return true;
    }
};

ll kruskal(int n, vector<Edge>& edges) {       // Edge{u, v, w}
    sort(edges.begin(), edges.end(), [](auto& a, auto& b){ return a.w < b.w; });
    DSU dsu(n);
    ll cost = 0; int used = 0;
    for (auto& e : edges) {
        if (dsu.unite(e.u, e.v)) { cost += e.w; if (++used == n - 1) break; }
    }
    return cost;   // used < n-1 ⇒ graph disconnected, no spanning tree
}
```

Complexity: $O(E \\log E)$, dominated by the sort. Path compression + union by rank makes each DSU call effectively $O(1)$.

**Prim**: instead of scanning a global edge list, grow one connected blob from any start node, always grabbing the cheapest edge that crosses *out of* the blob. It is literally the Dijkstra skeleton with one change — the heap is keyed on **edge weight**, not accumulated path distance.

```cpp
ll prim(int n, vector<vector<pair<int,int>>>& adj) { // adj[u]={v,w}
    vector<bool> inMST(n, false);
    priority_queue<pli, vector<pli>, greater<pli>> pq; // (edgeWeight, node)
    pq.push({0, 0});
    ll cost = 0; int cnt = 0;
    while (!pq.empty() && cnt < n) {
        auto [w, u] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        if (inMST[u]) continue;
        inMST[u] = true; cost += w; cnt++;
        for (auto [v, wt] : adj[u])
            if (!inMST[v]) pq.push({wt, v});
    }
    return cnt == n ? cost : -1;   // -1 ⇒ disconnected
}
```

> [!KEY] Which one, when?
> **Kruskal** when the input is already an edge list or the graph is sparse ($O(E \\log E)$). **Prim** when the graph is dense — e.g. *Min Cost to Connect All Points* gives you a complete graph of $V^2$ Manhattan-distance edges, exactly Prim territory ($O(E \\log V)$). Either passes typical constraints; naming the trade-off is the interview win.

deepdives.answer:
**The trap.** Your reflex says Dijkstra — weighted, non-negative, shortest path. But Dijkstra's core promise, *once a node is popped its distance is final*, assumes cost is the only thing that matters. Here there's a **second resource**: stops. The globally cheapest way to reach some airport might burn too many stops to ever continue to `dst`, while a *more expensive* route with fewer hops keeps the journey alive. Finalizing on price alone throws away exactly the paths you may need.

> [!INTUITION] Two currencies, one heap
> Dijkstra can only optimize one currency. When a problem prices paths in two (cost **and** hops), either expand the state to (node, hops) — or use a tool whose passes naturally count edges.

**The fix — Bellman-Ford, capped.** A path with at most K stops has at most **K+1 edges**. Each Bellman-Ford pass extends shortest paths by at most one edge, so run exactly K+1 passes. The one subtlety: relax against distances **frozen from the previous pass**. Relax in place, and one pass can chain an edge you *just* improved this round — sneaking multiple new edges into a single pass and blowing the hop budget.

[[fig:m11-bf-frozen]]

```cpp
int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int K) {
    vector<int> dist(n, INT_MAX);
    dist[src] = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i <= K; i++) {          // K stops ⇒ K+1 edges
        vector<int> tmp = dist;             // <-- freeze: read old, write new
        for (auto& f : flights) {
            int u = f[0], v = f[1], w = f[2];
            if (dist[u] != INT_MAX && dist[u] + w < tmp[v])
                tmp[v] = dist[u] + w;
        }
        dist = tmp;
    }
    return dist[dst] == INT_MAX ? -1 : dist[dst];
}
```

The `tmp` copy **is** the whole trick — drop it and you silently allow K+1 stops instead of K. **Time $O(K \\cdot E)$, space $O(V)$.**

**What generalizes:** any "shortest path with a budget on edges/uses/passes" bends to the same pattern — pass-limited relaxation over a frozen snapshot. It's also your template for "can this be done within K rounds?" DP-on-graphs questions.

**Why naive fails.** BFS ignores weights entirely, and standard Dijkstra minimizes the **sum** of steps — but this path's cost is its single **worst** step: the tallest cliff you climb, or the highest water you must wait for. Summing gives you the wrong objective, not just the wrong number.

[[fig:m11-minimax-path]]

> [!KEY] Dijkstra only needs monotonicity
> The finalization guarantee doesn't secretly depend on `+`. It needs one property of the relaxation: **extending a path never makes it better**. `dist[u] + w` has it (non-negative w). But so does `max(dist[u], w)` — a bottleneck can only stay equal or rise as the path grows. Swap the relaxation, keep everything else: heap, stale skip, finalization.

**The algorithm:** run the exact Dijkstra skeleton on the grid; the "distance" of a cell is the smallest possible maximum-step needed to reach it. Bonus: the first time you *pop* the target cell, its bottleneck is final — return immediately.

```cpp
int minimumEffortPath(vector<vector<int>>& h) {
    int m = h.size(), n = h[0].size();
    vector<vector<int>> eff(m, vector<int>(n, INT_MAX));
    priority_queue<array<int,3>, vector<array<int,3>>, greater<>> pq; // (effort, r, c)
    eff[0][0] = 0; pq.push({0, 0, 0});
    int dr[] = {0,0,1,-1}, dc[] = {1,-1,0,0};
    while (!pq.empty()) {
        auto [e, r, c] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        if (r == m-1 && c == n-1) return e;   // first time we pop the target = answer
        if (e > eff[r][c]) continue;
        for (int k = 0; k < 4; k++) {
            int nr = r + dr[k], nc = c + dc[k];
            if (nr<0||nc<0||nr>=m||nc>=n) continue;
            int cost = max(e, abs(h[nr][nc] - h[r][c]));  // bottleneck relaxation
            if (cost < eff[nr][nc]) { eff[nr][nc] = cost; pq.push({cost, nr, nc}); }
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

**Time $O(V \\log V)$ with $V = m \\cdot n$.** *Swim in Rising Water* is the identical idea — relax with `max(dist[u], grid[nr][nc])`.

**What generalizes:** any "minimize the maximum / maximize the minimum along a path" is minimax-Dijkstra. And name the alternative in interviews: it's also a **union-find + binary-search-on-answer** problem — "is there a path using only cells ≤ T?" is monotone in T — a great second solution to mention out loud.

**The setup.** "Minimum walls to break", "minimum sign flips to travel", "min obstacles removed": every move costs **0 or 1**. Dijkstra is correct here but drags an $O(\\log V)$ heap cost through every operation — overhead you don't need for two possible weights.

**The trick.** With weights in {0, 1}, the frontier only ever contains nodes at two distances, $d$ and $d+1$. A **deque** keeps them sorted for free: a 0-cost edge keeps the neighbor at distance $d$ → push **front** (handle before any $d+1$ node); a 1-cost edge → push **back**. Pops come out in nondecreasing distance order — the exact invariant that makes Dijkstra correct — with zero heap operations, so the whole thing runs in **$O(V + E)$**.

[[fig:m11-01bfs-deque]]

```cpp
// Minimum Obstacle Removal to Reach Corner: '1' cells cost 1 to enter, '0' cost 0
int minObstacles(vector<vector<int>>& g) {
    int m = g.size(), n = g[0].size();
    vector<vector<int>> dist(m, vector<int>(n, INT_MAX));
    deque<pair<int,int>> dq;
    dist[0][0] = 0; dq.push_front({0, 0});
    int dr[]={0,0,1,-1}, dc[]={1,-1,0,0};
    while (!dq.empty()) {
        auto [r, c] = dq.front(); dq.pop_front();
        for (int k = 0; k < 4; k++) {
            int nr=r+dr[k], nc=c+dc[k];
            if (nr<0||nc<0||nr>=m||nc>=n) continue;
            int w = g[nr][nc];                 // 0 or 1
            if (dist[r][c] + w < dist[nr][nc]) {
                dist[nr][nc] = dist[r][c] + w;
                if (w == 0) dq.push_front({nr, nc});
                else        dq.push_back({nr, nc});
            }
        }
    }
    return dist[m-1][n-1];
}
```

**Time $O(V + E)$, space $O(V)$** — on an $m \\times n$ grid that's $O(mn)$.

> [!EXAM]
> The sentence to say in an interview: *"weights are 0/1, so I'll use 0-1 BFS with a deque for $O(V+E)$ instead of Dijkstra's $O(E \\log V)$."* It signals real fluency — you chose the sharper tool and can justify it.

**What generalizes:** multi-source BFS (*01 Matrix*) uses the same skeleton with several starting cells at distance 0; and the deque idea extends to weights in {0, k} whenever only two edge costs exist.
